{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480227"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"27"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/27"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.25,0.51,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"27"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/27"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"27"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75721"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"105"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31592"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless ulcer on the medial aspect of her right shin. The ulcer has been present for two months. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The ulcer is examined (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following associated physical signs is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absent ankle jerk reflex","Diminished sensation to pinprick on the right foot","Superficial varicosities in the right leg","Absent dorsalis pedis pulse","Absent posterior tibial pulse"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic venous ulcer, characterised by its location in the gaiter area (between ankle and knee), shallow depth, and surrounding haemosiderin staining from chronic venous hypertension. Whilst venous ulcers are often open and weeping, in this instance a scab has formed over the ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial varicosities\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly associated with venous ulcers as they reflect the underlying pathophysiology of chronic venous insufficiency, which leads to venous hypertension and subsequent tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent ankle jerk reflex\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ediminished sensation to pinprick\u003C/strong\u003E are features of peripheral neuropathy, which typically causes ulcers over pressure points and bony prominences, particularly on the plantar aspect of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent dorsalis pedis pulse\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsent posterior tibial pulse\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest arterial insufficiency. Arterial ulcers typically occur at the most distal points of arterial supply such as toes or heel, are painful, and have a punched-out appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of haemosiderin staining (brown discolouration) around the ulcer is pathognomonic of chronic venous disease, caused by extravasation of red blood cells into the dermis due to increased venous pressure. Management typically includes compression therapy and elevation of the affected limb.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venous ulcers typically occur in the gaiter area of the leg due to chronic venous insufficiency","Venous ulcers are characterised by surrounding haemosiderin staining and erythema","Varicose veins are commonly associated with venous ulcers due to underlying chronic venous insufficiency."],"references":["Abbade LP, Last\u00f3ria S, Rollo Hde A. Venous ulcer: clinical characteristics and risk factors. Int J Dermatol. 2011 Apr;50(4):405-11. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21413949/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75721"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"27"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16264"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16264"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/11c7e985-8a37-4c55-a70b-40aca96d3362.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/11c7e985-8a37-4c55-a70b-40aca96d3362.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75721"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T16:37:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T16:37:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"27"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r